<paragraph blockId="5.[169,1155,988,1272]" box="[169,295,1063,1086]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis box="[169,295,1063,1086]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[169,1155,988,1272]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">
Habitus 
<figureCitation box="[286,393,1090,1112]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[161,198,1315,1337]" captionTargetBox="[177,1039,169,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[167,1072,138,1305]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 4. — Bambara spp. Bambara fragilis sp. n., A, habitus; Ba, Bb, spermathecae. Bambara lyrae sp. n., C, habitus; D, spermatheca.?Bambara problematica Darby, E, spermatheca.?Bambara subjoannis Darby, F, spermatheca. Bambara magnifica Darby, G, spermatheca. Bambara gabela Darby, H, spermatheca. Bambara frosti (Dybas), I, spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3653792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3653792/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Fig. 4C, L</figureCitation>
. 
<quantity box="[403,490,1090,1112]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.62">0.62mm</quantity>
. Yellow species, closely covered with pale pubescence, longer on the head, the antennae very pale almost translucent. Antennomeres III–XI L. 
<quantity box="[956,1043,1117,1139]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.23">0.23mm</quantity>
. Eyes very small, distance across eyes 
<quantity box="[465,552,1144,1166]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.19">0.19mm</quantity>
. Pronotum L. 
<quantity box="[709,796,1144,1166]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.16">0.16mm</quantity>
, W. 
<quantity box="[849,935,1144,1166]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.31">0.31mm</quantity>
, hind corners barely projected rearwards in dorsal view. Elytra L. 
<quantity box="[640,726,1170,1192]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.38">0.38mm</quantity>
, W. 
<quantity box="[774,861,1170,1192]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="0.32">0.32mm</quantity>
. with very short and narrow epipleura. Mesoventrum reticulate, without pubescence, keel very sharp between mesocoxae stopping short anteriorly of collar. Metaventrum reticulate and pubescent, coxae adjacent. Fully winged. 
<specimenCount box="[257,276,1250,1272]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">♀</specimenCount>
, spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[430,512,1250,1272]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[161,198,1315,1337]" captionTargetBox="[177,1039,169,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[167,1072,138,1305]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 4. — Bambara spp. Bambara fragilis sp. n., A, habitus; Ba, Bb, spermathecae. Bambara lyrae sp. n., C, habitus; D, spermatheca.?Bambara problematica Darby, E, spermatheca.?Bambara subjoannis Darby, F, spermatheca. Bambara magnifica Darby, G, spermatheca. Bambara gabela Darby, H, spermatheca. Bambara frosti (Dybas), I, spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3653792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3653792/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). 
<specimenCount box="[531,552,1250,1272]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">♂</specimenCount>
, not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="244" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[169,1154,1292,1662]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis box="[169,294,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Etymology</emphasis>
: Named in memory of Lyra McKee, the journalist recently shot dead by accident in 
<collectingCountry box="[306,393,1322,1348]" name="Ireland" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Ireland</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="244" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[169,1154,1292,1662]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis box="[169,288,1366,1392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The smallest of the Ugandan 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vuillet" authorityYear="1911" box="[691,800,1366,1392]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Bambara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[691,800,1366,1392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Bambara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Determined by the distinctive form of the spermatheca, which is only likely to be confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Darby" authorityName="Darby" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Bambara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verecunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">B. verecunda</emphasis>
Darby
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[441,583,1428,1454]" name="Madagascar" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and the widespread 
<taxonomicName authority="(Britten)" baseAuthorityName="Britten" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[823,1061,1428,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Bambara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunnea">
<emphasis box="[823,953,1428,1454]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">B. brunnea</emphasis>
(Britten)
</taxonomicName>
– but is distinguished from both those species by the reversed positions of the terminal arms of the receptacle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
